# Copilot Prompt and Instruction Setup on a New Mac (VS Code + Rider)

This guide explains how to move your current Copilot instruction/prompt setup to a new computer and keep it reproducible.

## What to migrate

From your current machine:

- Custom global Copilot instructions (you have this)
- Optional custom VS Code prompts folder (you can add this)

Do **not** migrate full runtime/state folders like `.copilot/session-state`.

## 1. Create a small config repo

On your current machine, create a repo like this:

```text
ai-config/
  copilot/
    instructions/
      copilot-instructions.md
  vscode/
    prompts/
  bootstrap.sh
```

## 2. Copy your current instruction file into that repo

```bash
cp ~/.copilot/instructions/copilot-instructions.md /path/to/ai-config/copilot/instructions/
```

## 3. (Optional) Create a prompts folder in the repo

If you want reusable custom prompt files:

```bash
mkdir -p /path/to/ai-config/vscode/prompts
```

## 4. Commit and push the config repo

```bash
cd /path/to/ai-config
git init
git add .
git commit -m "Add Copilot machine setup"
git branch -M main
git remote add origin <your-private-repo-url>
git push -u origin main
```

## 5. On the new Mac, install prerequisites

Install and sign in to:

- VS Code
- Rider
- Git
- GitHub account
- GitHub Copilot in VS Code and Rider

## 6. Clone your config repo on the new Mac

```bash
git clone <your-private-repo-url> ~/ai-config
```

## 7. Restore global Copilot instructions location

```bash
mkdir -p ~/.copilot/instructions
ln -sf ~/ai-config/copilot/instructions/copilot-instructions.md ~/.copilot/instructions/copilot-instructions.md
```

## 8. Prepare VS Code prompts path (linked to repo)

```bash
mkdir -p "$HOME/Library/Application Support/Code/User"
mkdir -p "$HOME/ai-config/vscode/prompts"
ln -sfn "$HOME/ai-config/vscode/prompts" "$HOME/Library/Application Support/Code/User/prompts"
```

## 9. Install required VS Code extensions

```bash
code --install-extension GitHub.copilot
code --install-extension GitHub.copilot-chat
code --install-extension GitHub.vscode-pull-request-github
```

## 10. Configure Rider

In Rider:

1. Install/enable the GitHub Copilot plugin.
2. Sign in with the same GitHub account.
3. Restart Rider.

## 11. Validate setup

1. Restart VS Code and Rider.
2. Open Copilot Chat in VS Code.
3. Ask a simple prompt and confirm behavior follows your custom instructions.

## 12. Make setup one-command with bootstrap.sh

Create `bootstrap.sh` in your `ai-config` repo:

```bash
#!/usr/bin/env bash
set -euo pipefail

mkdir -p ~/.copilot/instructions
ln -sf "$HOME/ai-config/copilot/instructions/copilot-instructions.md" ~/.copilot/instructions/copilot-instructions.md

mkdir -p "$HOME/Library/Application Support/Code/User"
mkdir -p "$HOME/ai-config/vscode/prompts"
ln -sfn "$HOME/ai-config/vscode/prompts" "$HOME/Library/Application Support/Code/User/prompts"

if command -v code >/dev/null 2>&1; then
  code --install-extension GitHub.copilot || true
  code --install-extension GitHub.copilot-chat || true
  code --install-extension GitHub.vscode-pull-request-github || true
fi
```

Make it executable and run:

```bash
chmod +x ~/ai-config/bootstrap.sh
~/ai-config/bootstrap.sh
```

## Important notes

- Built-in Copilot prompt/skill files are shipped by extensions; do not copy them manually.
- Keep only your own stable config in the repo (instructions, prompt templates, optional editor settings).
- Use a private repo for personal setup files.
